The Lagos State Government has empowered 217 beneficiaries under its social inclusion programme, Eko Cares Initiative, as a means of empowering indigent members of the State for economic independence and self-sufficiency. The initiative, aimed at actualising the ‘Greater Lagos’ project of Governor Babajide Sanwo-Olu’s administration, is designed as a form of financial assistance to 2,000 beneficiaries from all the Local Government Areas (LGAs) and Local Council Development Areas (LCDAs) across the state with the sum of N20,000 to invest in economic activities that would guarantee a quick turnover. Governor Sanwo-Olu had at the flag-off of the initiative in December 2019, said it would be in phases with the business component to make a lot of people self-reliant and contribute to the economic growth of the State. Sanwo-Olu, Canadian Mayor discuss cooperation in ICT, food security Sanwo-Olu to mark one year in office with virtual, on-site commissioning of projects Why we’re investing N25bn in Smart Lagos – MainOne CEO